<paragraph blockId="55.[151,1436,152,1418]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<emphasis box="[198,274,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">Notes:</emphasis>
This species was originally described by 
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin, R. V." box="[766,990,712,738]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" pagination="149 - 152" refId="ref39950" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1946) On some millipeds of Georgia. Entomological News, 58, 149 - 152." type="journal article" year="1946">Chamberlin (1946)</bibRefCitation>
as a subspecies of 
<emphasis box="[1215,1361,712,737]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName box="[1215,1357,712,737]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="austrinus">S. austrinus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
based only on the lack of a claw on the ninth leg in 
<emphasis box="[700,777,752,777]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[700,774,752,777]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nudus">nudus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
This is a trivial character, since the claw is missing in most specimens of male 
<emphasis box="[443,567,792,817]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName box="[443,559,792,817]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scoterpes</taxonomicName>
;
</emphasis>
Loomis’ 1943 illustration happened to be of a specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[1275,1384,792,817]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="austrinus">
<emphasis box="[1275,1384,792,817]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">austrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that had a vestigial claw. In 1972, I speculated that the subspecific designation might not be valid; Hoffman (2000) then placed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[378,448,872,897]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nudus">
<emphasis box="[378,448,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">nudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the synonymy of 
<emphasis box="[691,806,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName box="[691,803,872,897]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="austrinus">austrinus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
citing my mention of a specimen of typical 
<taxonomicName box="[1327,1436,872,897]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="austrinus">
<emphasis box="[1327,1436,872,897]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">austrinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from White River Cave in Floyd County. Unfortunately we were both wrong; White River Cave is actually in Bartow County, but in any case is south of the Oostanaula River and therefore geographically proves nothing about the identity of 
<emphasis box="[419,496,992,1017]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[419,493,992,1017]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nudus">nudus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Distributional data aside from 
<typeStatus box="[877,927,992,1018]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">type</typeStatus>
localities was not available in 1971 or in 2000. I stated that I had not compared my specimens to the 
<typeStatus box="[871,922,1032,1058]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">type</typeStatus>
of 
<emphasis box="[963,1040,1032,1057]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[963,1036,1032,1057]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nudus">nudus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
and did not formalize the synonymy, but my illustrations (1972: figs. 518–520) clearly depict 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[890,960,1072,1097]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nudus">
<emphasis box="[890,960,1072,1097]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">nudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the microteeth on the lateral or ectal coxite; that distinction is made for the first time here. The two species are obviously very close, and subspecies designation for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Chamberlin" authorityYear="2010" baseAuthorityName="Chamberlin" baseAuthorityYear="1946" box="[470,540,1152,1177]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nudus">
<emphasis box="[470,540,1152,1177]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">nudus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may still prove to be correct if intermediate populations are found between the compact distributions now known for the two nominal species. At present, since both populations are distinct morphologically and geographically, regarding them both as full species best fits the evidence. Clearly 
<bibRefCitation author="Chamberlin, R. V." box="[151,376,1272,1298]" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" pagination="149 - 152" refId="ref39950" refString="Chamberlin, R. V. (1946) On some millipeds of Georgia. Entomological News, 58, 149 - 152." type="journal article" year="1946">Chamberlin (1946)</bibRefCitation>
did not have a modern view of the category subspecies, which at the time he wrote was still inextricably confused with the concept of “variety.” Solving the status of the two populations would be a nice little problem for a local naturalist. For additional information, see the Notes on 
<emphasis box="[1180,1327,1352,1377]" italics="true" pageId="55" pageNumber="56">
<taxonomicName box="[1180,1323,1352,1377]" class="Diplopoda" family="Trichopetalidae" genus="Scoterpes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Chordeumatida" pageId="55" pageNumber="56" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="austrinus">S. austrinus</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
immediately above.
</paragraph>
